Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Soak your @bamboo skewers{4} in cold water (this will prevent them from burning).

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} lengthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm wide chips (no need to peel).

Pop the chips onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with oil, sprinkle over the @white cumin seeds{1%sachet}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, cut the @paneer{226%grams} into 2cm cubes.

Halve and peel the @red onion{1}(peeled), then cut each half into 4 wedges.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine the @tikka masala paste{75%grams} with a drizzle of oil, the @salt{1/4%tsp} and @honey{2%tbsp}. Mix in half the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%grams} and season with @pepper{}.

Add the paneer and onion wedges to the marinade. Toss until coated.

Carefully thread the paneer and onion wedges onto the skewers (2 per person), alternating between the two.

Pop the skewers onto a #lined baking tray{} and bake on the middle shelf of your oven until golden, ~{15-18%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, trim and peel the @carrot{1}(trimmed and peeled). Use the #peeler{} to peel long ribbons down the length of the carrot, stopping at the core.

Clean the (now empty) paneer bowl, then add the @red wine vinegar{12%ml}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @olive oil{1%tbsp} for the dressing to the bowl. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add the carrot ribbons to the dressing, toss to coat, then set aside to pickle.

When everything's ready, add the @baby leaf mix{20%grams} to the carrot ribbons and toss to coat.

> TIP: Don't add the leaves too early or they'll go soggy.

Share the tikka skewers between your plates and drizzle over the remaining yoghurt to finish.

Serve the cumin seed chips and carrot salad alongside. Enjoy!